1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:04,700
What if a game did not only test what you know, but showed how the world fits together?

2
00:00:05,500 --> 00:00:11,100
This is Webwoven, a game about finding paths through real, named connections.

3
00:00:11,700 --> 00:00:15,600
In Single player, I pick an easy, normal, or hard route.

4
00:00:16,100 --> 00:00:19,300
I can leave the map open, or choose one of ten topics.

5
00:00:19,900 --> 00:00:24,100
Each round gives me a start, a goal, and a best distance.

6
00:00:24,800 --> 00:00:26,400
Now I find my own path.

7
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:28,900
Each card is a place I can go next.

8
00:00:29,300 --> 00:00:31,400
When I move, the map grows.

9
00:00:31,800 --> 00:00:34,300
It keeps my path and the choices I left behind.

10
00:00:34,800 --> 00:00:37,700
Three hints can help, but each costs points.

11
00:00:38,400 --> 00:00:40,600
Each card also explains its connection.

12
00:00:41,100 --> 00:00:44,800
Here, Lionel Messi connects to Rosario because he was born there.

13
00:00:45,400 --> 00:00:49,700
I can read the fact, see its picture, and check the source before I move.

14
00:00:50,500 --> 00:00:52,500
Webwoven has three play modes.

15
00:00:52,900 --> 00:00:55,400
Single player lets me explore at my own speed.

16
00:00:55,900 --> 00:00:59,100
The Daily challenge gives everyone the same route and scoreboard.

17
00:00:59,800 --> 00:01:03,000
Multiplayer lets two to four people race on the same map.

18
00:01:03,400 --> 00:01:06,100
Players can leave and return without losing the room.

19
00:01:06,900 --> 00:01:09,900
I started with a game idea, but no working product.

20
00:01:10,400 --> 00:01:15,200
I built the main product with Codex, using GPT-5.6 Sol.

21
00:01:15,700 --> 00:01:19,600
I gave Codex the goals, visual style, and play-test feedback.

22
00:01:20,100 --> 00:01:25,400
Codex helped build the app, server, data tools, tests, and public documents.

23
00:01:25,900 --> 00:01:29,900
It split large jobs into focused tasks for the web, server,

24
00:01:30,100 --> 00:01:32,100
data, security, and review.

25
00:01:32,600 --> 00:01:35,200
This saved time while keeping each part clear.

26
00:01:35,700 --> 00:01:39,400
I kept using GPT-5.6 after the first draft.

27
00:01:39,800 --> 00:01:44,300
I played on desktop and phone, found problems, and gave them back to Codex.

28
00:01:44,900 --> 00:01:52,300
We made the play modes easier to find, removed unfair loops, improved the fact text,
and rebuilt the phone map for touch.

29
00:01:52,900 --> 00:01:57,000
I made the final product, design, data, and release choices.

30
00:01:57,600 --> 00:02:00,800
AI helped build Webwoven, but it does not play for you.

31
00:02:01,400 --> 00:02:04,800
During a round, there are no calls to AI or Wikidata.

32
00:02:05,400 --> 00:02:11,200
Rules, moves, hints, scores, and winners come from one checked local map.

33
00:02:11,600 --> 00:02:17,800
It contains 3,970 things and more than 22,000 named connections.

34
00:02:18,500 --> 00:02:25,200
Webwoven is live, works on desktop and mobile, needs no account, and is completely open-source.

35
00:02:25,700 --> 00:02:28,700
Connect anything, and discover why it is connected.
